{"id":14881511,"mediaExerciseId":"f138bb53-cb83-44e3-8503-aafb796e590d","exerciseName":"9","chapterName":"15","chapterTitle":"Raising Capital","groupId":612403,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":529,"solutions":[{"id":6048463,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to assess the IPO underpricing. \n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The act of issuing an initial public offering (IPO) at a price less than its true market value on the public market is known as **underpricing**.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**The investor has made a loss because he is unable to participate in an oversubscribed IPO that is often underpriced**. When the investor has invested in an oversubscribed IPO, that indicates that the investor was willing to purchase the company's stock, resulting in a greater price and a more significant number of shares available for purchase.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"**In this situation, the investor subscribes to an overpriced investment, which is bad for their investment portfolio since it might lead to a significant decline in the value**, even if the higher price helps the investment bank that issued the stock. \n\nThe investor is overpaying for securities because the demand for a particular issuance is lower than the number of shares issued by the company. \n\n**As a result, the investor's return is lower than planned.**\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"54cd18c6-3085-4f75-af50-7c6b071df36f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881512,"exerciseName":"10","page":530,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"8f4bd1f9-c91c-4b0b-ab08-648d3f9aad46","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-15-critical-thinking-questions-10-8f4bd1f9-c91c-4b0b-ab08-648d3f9aad46"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881510,"exerciseName":"8","page":529,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"6d832f9c-2524-48be-99c0-15c940bc7224","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-15-critical-thinking-questions-8-6d832f9c-2524-48be-99c0-15c940bc7224"},{"id":14881509,"exerciseName":"7","page":529,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"bf794185-7860-4957-96df-d0d5348ef477","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-15-critical-thinking-questions-7-bf794185-7860-4957-96df-d0d5348ef477"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-15-critical-thinking-questions-9-f138bb53-cb83-44e3-8503-aafb796e590d"}